🚀 Reproduction Steps
1. Cluster Initialization & Deployment
First, ensure your Kubernetes cluster (Kind/Minikube) is running within Docker, then deploy the application:

Bash
# Apply the tutorial deployment (replace with your actual file if you have one)
kubectl create deployment my-app --image=nginx

# Verify the initial rollout
kubectl get deployments
kubectl get pods
2. Networking & Verification
To access the application from your Windows browser, establish a tunnel from your WSL terminal:

Bash
# Forward traffic from local port 8080 to the container's port 80
kubectl port-forward deployment/my-app 8080:80
Note: Keep this terminal open and visit http://localhost:8080 to generate traffic.

3. Scaling for High Availability
Simulate a traffic spike or redundancy by scaling the application to multiple replicas:

Bash
# Scale the deployment to 3 pods
kubectl scale deployment/my-app --replicas=3

# Verify the pods are distributed and running
kubectl get pods -o wide
4. Observability & Request Tracing
To identify exactly which pod and node are serving your live requests, use these debugging commands:

Bash
# Stream aggregated logs from all replicas with pod name prefixes
kubectl logs -l app=my-app --tail=10 -f --prefix

# In a separate terminal, map the pod name from the logs to its host node
kubectl get pods -o wide


# Shutdown
#stop  Port forwarding 
ps aux| grep port-forward - you get grep pid too
ps aux| grep [p]ort-forward - avoid grep pid
kill <PID>

#All powerful 
pkill -f "kubectl port-forward"



# shutdown cluster
kubectl scale deployment/my-app --replicas=0

kubectl delete deployment/my-app

